GAMLSS Modeling with Advanced Flexible Infrastructures

Mikis Stasinopoulos, Robert Rigby, Nikolaus Umlauf

Overview

The primary purpose of this package is to facilitate the creation of advanced infrastructures designed to enhance the GAMLSS modeling framework. Notably, the gamlss2 package represents a significant overhaul of its predecessor, gamlss, with a key emphasis on improving estimation speed and incorporating more flexible infrastructures. These enhancements enable the seamless integration of various algorithms into GAMLSS, including gradient boosting, Bayesian estimation, regression trees, and forests, fostering a more versatile and powerful modeling environment.

Moreover, the package expands its compatibility by supporting all model terms from the base R mgcv package. Additionally, the gamlss2 package introduces the capability to accommodate more than four parameter families. Essentially, this means that users can now specify any type of model using these new infrastructures, making the package highly flexible and accommodating to a wide range of modeling requirements.

Installation

The development version of gamlss2 is hosted on github at https://github.com/gamlss-dev/gamlss2. It can be installed via

devtools::install_github("gamlss-dev/gamlss2")

Introduction

This section gives a first quick overview of the functionality of the package and demonstrates that the usual “look & feel” when using well-established model fitting functions like glm() is an elementary part of gamlss2, i.e., first steps and basic handling of the package should be relatively simple. We illustrate the first steps with gamlss2 using a data set taken from the Regression Book (Fahrmeir et al. 2021) which is about prices of used VW Golf cars. The data is loaded with

data("Golf", package = "bamlss")
head(Golf)
##   price age kilometer tia abs sunroof
## 1  7.30  73        10  12 yes     yes
## 2  3.85 115        30  20 yes      no
## 3  2.95 127        43   6  no     yes
## 4  4.80 104        54  25 yes     yes
## 5  6.20  86        57  23  no      no
## 6  5.90  74        57  25 yes      no

In this example the aim is to model the price in 1000 Euro. Using gamlss2 a first linear model could be set up by first specifying a model formula

f <- price ~ age + kilometer + tia + abs + sunroof

afterwards the model is estimated by

library("gamlss2")
b1 <- gamlss2(f, family = NO, data = Golf)
## GAMLSS-RS iteration  1: Global Deviance = 394.949 eps = 0.298244    
GAMLSS-RS iteration  2: Global Deviance = 394.949 eps = 0.000000

Munich Rent GAMLSS

To illustrate the functionality of the gamlss2 package, we use the rent99 dataset, which is included in the gamlss.data package.

data("rent99", package = "gamlss.data")

We estimate models using the GA distribution.

## Model formula.
f <- rent ~ s(area) + s(yearc) + location + bath + kitchen |
   s(area) + s(yearc) + location + bath + kitchen

## Estimation.
start <- proc.time()
b1 <- gamlss2(f, data = rent99, family = GA)
## GAMLSS-RS iteration  1: Global Deviance = 38445.7719 eps = 0.055723    
GAMLSS-RS iteration  2: Global Deviance = 38419.413 eps = 0.000685    
GAMLSS-RS iteration  3: Global Deviance = 38419.1931 eps = 0.000005
proc.time() - start
##    user  system elapsed 
##   0.434   0.000   0.434
## Estimation with gamlss.
start <- proc.time()
b2 <- gamlss(rent ~ pb(area) + pb(yearc) + location + bath + kitchen,
  sigma.formula =~ pb(area) + pb(yearc) + location + bath + kitchen,
  data = rent99, family = GA)
## GAMLSS-RS iteration 1: Global Deviance = 38459.65 
## GAMLSS-RS iteration 2: Global Deviance = 38448.8 
## GAMLSS-RS iteration 3: Global Deviance = 38448.64 
## GAMLSS-RS iteration 4: Global Deviance = 38448.62 
## GAMLSS-RS iteration 5: Global Deviance = 38448.62
proc.time() - start
##    user  system elapsed 
##   7.355   0.028   7.382
## Compare using the AIC.
AIC(b1, b2)
##          df      AIC
## b1 36.52459 38492.24
## b2 25.38180 38499.38

Note that gamlss2 is considerably faster in this example. Estimated effects can be visualized with

plot(b1)

term.plot(b2, what = "mu", pages = 1, ask = FALSE)

term.plot(b2, what = "sigma", pages = 1, ask = FALSE)

Big Data

To optimize computational efficiency when working with large datasets, we leverage the observation that the number of distinct observations for a given covariate is typically significantly smaller than the total number of observations in the complete dataset. As a strategy, we calculate design matrices only using these unique observations and implement the exceptionally efficient algorithms presented in Lang et al. (2012). This option can be used by setting the argument binning = TRUE. In many instances, it is feasible to decrease the number of distinct observations through rounding, such as rounding to two digits. In the context of large datasets, the approximation error associated with this rounding is typically negligible.

Below, we present an example utilizing precipitation data obtained from German meteorological stations, provided by the Deutscher Wetterdienst (DWD, https://www.dwd.de/). In this illustration, we employ a censored normal distribution to model precipitation amounts, which can be constructed using the gamlss.cens package.

library("gamlss.cens")
gen.cens(NO, type = "left")
## A censored family of distributions from NO has been generated 
##  and saved under the names:  
##  dNOlc pNOlc qNOlc NOlc 
## The type of censoring is left

The compiled data set is available at WeatherGermany.rds and contains the following covariates

d <- readRDS("WeatherGermany.rds")
print(dim(d))
## [1] 1187507      12
print(head(d))
##       ID   Name       Date year mon yday alt    lon     lat    T  Pre Wmax
## 44742  3 Aachen 1981-01-01 1981   0    0 202 6.0941 50.7827  3.4  4.5 20.6
## 44743  3 Aachen 1981-01-02 1981   0    1 202 6.0941 50.7827  5.8 17.6 19.6
## 44744  3 Aachen 1981-01-03 1981   0    2 202 6.0941 50.7827  6.6 10.6 27.3

## 44747  3 Aachen 1981-01-06 1981   0    5 202 6.0941 50.7827 -0.1  2.1 11.8

The model can be estimated with

## Create indicator for Surv() response.
d$cens <- d$Pre > 0

## Model formula.
f <- ~ s(year) + s(alt,k=4) +
  ti(yday,bs="cc") + ti(lon,lat,bs="tp",d=2,k=30) +
  ti(yday,lon,lat,bs=c("cc","tp"),d=c(1,2),k=c(10,30))

f <- rep(list(f), 2)
f[[1]] <- update(f[[1]], Surv(sqrt(Pre), cens, type = "left") ~ .)

## Estimate model.
b <- gamlss2(f, data = d, family = NOlc,
  binning = TRUE, light = TRUE, flush = FALSE)

Please be aware that setting the argument light = TRUE results in the exclusion of all design matrices, the model frame, and fitted values from the returned object. This is done to minimize the object’s size. Note that the model is quite complex, as it includes a three dimensional seasonal varying spatial effect.

The summary statistics gives

Exchanging the Optimizer

The default optimizer function in gamlss2 is RS(). The function has arguments

RS(x, y, specials, family, offsets, weights, xterms, sterms, control)

where x is the linear effects design matrix, y is the response (a vector or matrix), specials is a named list of special model terms, e.g., as created by smooth constructor s(). Now xterms and sterms are named lists, each list element represents one parameter of the distribution as specified in the family. One list elements holds the variable names of linear effects or the term labels of specials (smooth) model terms. This way, no duplicated design matrices need to be setup.

The return value of RS() is of class "gamlss2" for which summary, extractor and plotting functions are provided.

Note that function RS()may be exchanged, either using gamlss2_control() or if an $optimizer function is specified within the family. This way, one could also integrate full Bayesian MCMC methods, or boosting algorithms etc. Only the methods for the return value need to be written new for such functions.

New Special Terms

In similar fashion new “special” model terms can be included for RS()and GC(). All is needed is to write methods for

special_fit(x, ...)
special_predict(x, ...)

where x is a model term object as supplied in the formula in the gamlss2() call.

Example using existing smooth.construct() infrastructures, new pb2() model term

pb2 <- function(x, df = NULL, lambda = NULL, max.df = NULL, control = pb2.control(...), ...)
{
  m <- c(control$degree, control$order)
  k <- control$inter + m[1L] + 1L
  sx <- s(x, bs = "ps", m = m, k = k, sp = lambda)
  sx$control <- control
  sx$label <- gsub("s(", "pb2(", sx$label, fixed = TRUE)
  sx$orig.label <- sx$label
  sx$localML <- TRUE
  return(sx)
}

Or, completely new model term, e.g., conditional inference forest constructor.

## Special conditional inference forest constructor.
cf <- function(formula, ...)
{
  stopifnot(requireNamespace("partykit"))
  st <- list()
  ctr <- list(...)
  ntree <- ctr$ntree
  if(is.null(ntree))
    ntree <- 100L
  ctr$ntree <- NULL
  st$control <- do.call(partykit::ctree_control, ctr)
  st$formula <- formula
  st$term <- all.vars(formula)
  st$label <- paste0("cf(", paste0(gsub(" ", "", as.character(formula)), collapse = ""), ")")
  st$data <- model.frame(formula)
  st$ntree <- ntree
  class(st) <- c("special", "cf")
  return(st)
}

## The fitting function for the backfitting algorithm.
special_fit.cf <- function(x, z, w, y, eta, j, family, control, ...)
{
  f <- update(x$formula, response_z ~ .)
  x$data$response_z <- z
  rval <- list(
    "model" = partykit::cforest(formula = f, data = x$data, weights = w,
      control = x$control, ntree = x$ntree)
  )
  rval$fitted.values <- predict(rval$model)
  rval$shift <- mean(rval$fitted.values)
  rval$fitted.values <- rval$fitted.values - rval$shift
  rval$edf <- x$ntree
  class(rval) <- "cf.fitted"
  return(rval)
}

## Predict method.
special_predict.cf.fitted <- function(x, data, se.fit = FALSE, ...)
{
  if(se.fit) {
    ct <- lapply(seq_along(x$model$nodes), function(i) partykit::as.constparty(
      partykit::party(x$model$nodes[[i]], data = x$model$data, terms = x$model$terms,
      fitted = data.frame(
        `(response)` = x$model$fitted[["(response)"]],
        `(weights)` = x$model$weights[[i]],
        check.names = FALSE))
    ))
    p <- sapply(ct, predict, newdata = data)
    p <- apply(p, 1, quantile, prob = c(0.05, 0.5, 0.95))
    p <- t(p)
    colnames(p) <- c("lower", "fit", "upper")
  } else {
    p <- predict(x$model, newdata = data, type = "response")
  }
  p <- p - x$shift
  return(p)
}

Similar, a neural network model term, see ?special_terms.

Notes

  • Package gamlss “special” model terms in gamlss2? Support is already there but limited, e.g., using pb() confidence intervals cannot be computed.
  • Write wrappers like pb2(), use smooth.construct()?
  • Goal is to write more optimizer/sampler functions.
  • Project idea, “non-cyclic” algorithm for fast stepwise selection of linear or smooth terms?
  • predict() with confidence/prediction intervals? se.fit = TRUE does not work using new data?
  • How should we compute confidence/prediction intervals?
  • Considering gamlss, extend the examples similar to gamlss2.
  • Check the manual pages carefully, e.g., do we need references on every manual page?
  • Include the NO() distribution in gamlss (or hidden default .NO()) so we can write examples for each family in gamlss.dist?
